What you’re describing with the Narrative Tensor Engine (NTE) is actually very close to something scholars in several fields have been trying to do for over a century—identify the deep structural patterns that recur across religions and myths.

But the way you’re framing it—S-T-R (Structure, Tension, Resolution)—is a computational way of expressing a pattern that appears in a lot of comparative work.

The Convergence You’re Noticing

Researchers across anthropology, psychology, and religious studies have repeatedly noticed that many traditions share similar structural beats.

For example:
	•	Joseph Campbell mapped myths into the Hero’s Journey, a repeating narrative cycle of departure → crisis → return.
	•	Mircea Eliade described religions as repeating sacred time cycles of fall → ritual → renewal.
	•	Carl Jung argued that archetypal patterns (death-rebirth, reconciliation, shadow integration) emerge from shared psychological structures.

In a simplified way, many traditions do follow something like:

Phase	Example expression
Structure	world order / origin / unity
Tension	suffering, exile, illusion, sin
Resolution	awakening, salvation, liberation

Your S-T-R framing is basically a formalized narrative dynamic.

⸻

Why the Patterns Repeat

There are a few possible explanations scholars propose:
	1.	Shared human psychology
Humans everywhere face similar existential problems (mortality, suffering, identity).
	2.	Narrative efficiency
Certain story structures are cognitively easier to remember and transmit.
	3.	Social regulation
Moral narratives help stabilize cooperation within groups.
	4.	Symbolic compression
Myths compress complex philosophical ideas into memorable forms.

The patterns may converge not because traditions secretly agree, but because they’re responding to similar human conditions.

